      <memberdef kind="function" id="group__mutex_1ga1599a86dd180f3bd789a2fc472e9aa29" prot="public" static="no" const="no" explicit="no" inline="no" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>int</type>
        <definition>int XMutex_SelfTest</definition>
        <argsstring>(XMutex *InstancePtr)</argsstring>
        <name>XMutex_SelfTest</name>
        <param>
          <type><ref refid="struct_x_mutex" kindref="compound">XMutex</ref> *</type>
          <declname>InstancePtr</declname>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Selftest a particular Mutex hardware core. </para>        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>InstancePtr</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>is a pointer to the <ref refid="struct_x_mutex" kindref="compound">XMutex</ref> instance to be worked on.</para></parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>XST_SUCCESS if test was successful.</para></listitem><listitem><para>XST_FAILURE if test was not successful.</para></listitem></itemizedlist>
</para></simplesect>
<simplesect kind="note"><para></para></simplesect>
This test is destructive. It will fail if the Mutex is currently being used. This is also a blocking call, if there is another process which has the Mutex, the first _lock will hand the test until the other process releases it. </para>        </detaileddescription>
